node.text:
.
.
.
Bartender: “we don’t serve time travelers here”
.
.
.
....a time traveler walks into a bar 🤣🙃

.
.
.
Finally put together a how-to video on traveling with my tri bike! I travel a lot with my bikes and this is how I do it 😁
.
.
Feel free to share with a fellow 🚲 traveler!
.
.
.
#triathlete #triathlonlife #3athlonlife #tri365 #biketravel

node.title: How to pack your tri bike for travel!

node.text:
My first match at the Atlanta Open this year, following this I lost my second match to points leading me to win bronze 🥉 .
.
.
Had an interesting camp leading into this one 🤣 after Pans I did a few weeks of training then got sick, had to quarantine, then had one week back in the gym where I also did my 10 lbs weight cut 😓. 
.
.
My main goal for this open was to “rewire” some thought processes that got shifted from my experience competing at Pans only a month prior. At Pans I had a horrible base for standup, was incredibly scared of doing stand up and as a result I pulled the worst guard in the history of guard pulling then proceeded to get choked 0.2 seconds later 😂. 
.
.
Really happy as I started this match with a much stronger base, even though I got taken down I recovered my guard and was 100% able to play my game. 
.
.
.
My second match I lost on points but was really happy as it was a fun match (first time I’ve had “fun” while competing) where I found a lot of little holes in my game. I’m excited to go work on fixing things AND to get back to triathlon training 🏊🏻‍♀️ 🚴🏼 🏃🏻‍♀️ 
.
.
.
Huge thank you to everyone at my home gym @cfma_stalbert and my professor @antunkovacevic. Also a massive thank you to @profectusbjj and professor Jeremy, coach @fayyazbjj and all the training partners there 🥰 you all put so much extra time in teaching me and making sure I was ready to compete (and wouldn’t cry during the stand up) 
.
.
.
#bjjlifestyle #brazilianjiujitsu #ibjjfatlantaopen #bjjgirls #bjjwomen

....a sand witch 🥪🧙🏽‍♀️
.
.
Favourite terrain to run on? Beach? Track? Treadmill? Grass? Dirt paths? 
.
.
Flashback Friday to getting in some kms on the beautiful beaches in Australia! Really excited to hear that the 2022 worlds will be back in Australia!
.

node.text:
Do you prefer gold or silver?
.
.
...because for me it’s either ore 😜
.
.
Did you know that bronze medalists are often happier than silver medalists? 
.
.
Silver medalists make an upward comparison to the gold medalist whereas bronze medalists make a downward comparison...thinking “hey at least I got a medal!” 
.
.
Its interesting how athletes and coaches think about wins and losses. 
.
.
I often get asked what my best 70.3 ironman race time is and my response is “on what course?”...if I’m racing up a mountain I’m going to be slower than if I raced ironman Texas. Just like how I’m more proud of my silver medal at blue belt than I am of my gold medal at white belt. The blue matches were harder...I had to fight for that silver
.
.
When I competed in equestrian I placed 2nd in the world....yet I’m more proud of when I placed 7th in the world because I was on a hard horse...I had to WORK for that. YEARS of training and performing at 100% on game day. 
.
.
Stop measuring your worth as an athlete by the colour of your medal and start measuring by your performance.
.
.
Fight for gold, but don’t make your placing represent your skill and ability or you’ll forever be chasing an outcome that won’t make you as happy as you think....and will eventually cause you to burn out. 
.
.
Strive to PERFORM better. The happiness a gold medal gives you should be directly related to your performance leading up to earning that medal. If you didn’t perform well but still won...you probably shouldn’t be over the moon. Stop caring about the spray painted colour on some cheap medal. Care about your skill and performance as an athlete. 
.
.
And if you’re a coach, especially to young kids, work on instilling these values in them bc you will foster an intrinsically motivated athlete rather than an extrinsically motivated athlete. I was VERY lucky that my first coach valued hard work and performance rather than placings. If I won and shouldn’t have we did not celebrate. If I lost and shouldn’t have, he consoled me. It was always about my performance as an athlete...not on how I placed. 
.
.
Thoughts?
.
.
#sportspsychology #athlete #triathlete #jiujitsugirls #jiujitsugirl

node.text:
A dung beetle walks into a bar..
.
.
....looks around and then asks....”is this stool taken?” 
.
.
How many times a day do you....💩?
.
.
ALRIGHT IM ABOUT TO TALK ABOUT POOP. @colon.broom contacted me asking if I wanted to promote their product, like any product I’m asked to promote I need to try it out first and I will also give an honest review! So here goes!
.
.
First impression after my first week of trying out the @colon.broom fibre supplement! First of all, I’ve been on the road for the last few weeks traveling for competitions, and as most people know, traveling can get you a little....backed up 😐💩. 
.
@colon.broom is a fibre supplement which works as a prebiotic and helps nourish healthy gut bacteria....and in turn helps you poop. Obviously as an athlete it can definitely suck when you’re traveling to compete and you feel horrible because you can’t poop...and on top of it, being an athlete that competes in a sport where I need to make weight, being backed up can be the difference between me having to do a water cut or getting to go into my competition fully healthy. 
.
.
I’ve got another 2 months of traveling nearly every weekend (mostly for jiu jitsu competitions) and I’m really happy that I’ll have @colon.broom to take long with me. It’s just a powder that mixes in with water, and honestly tastes decent! 
.
.
For a discount head over to the link in my bio OR you can use my discount code: DANIELLE30 for $30 off a 3 or 6 month subscription. 
.
.
.

.

node.text:
What’s the opposite of Florida?
.
.
.
...the ceiling, duh 😜
.
.
Footage of my finish in the semi finals of the open weight bracket in no gi at the Orlando Summer Open 🌴
.
.
Happy that I was able to snag an arm for the finish, but learnt a lot in this match about things I need to work on. The reason I love competing so much is because everytime you compete you get the most realistic feedback on what you need to work on. 
.
.
Most of the time jiu jiteras and jiteros spend majority of their time training at their own gym so we get used to what works in our room and what doesn’t...the issue is, most gyms have a certain style so it doesn’t always give you a realistic look at where your jiu jitsu is at. 
.
.
Excited to get to drilling, working my conditioning, and strength training leading into pans and no gi worlds 
.
.
#jiujitsugirls #jiujitsugirl #bjjgirls #bjjlifestyle #bjjlife #jiujitsulife

node.text:
What’s an octopus’ favourite wrestling move?
.
.
...ten tackles 🐙 😂
.
.
.
First official blue belt tournament in the books! 
.
.
I’ll post competition footage later when I have better wifi but wanted to give a quick update! 
.
.
I lost my first match in the gi on the Thursday, but had a great match and learned a lot. Friday was no-gi, no one in my bracket so I went straight to the open weight! Was really happy to see a large open bracket and was able to snag silver in the end ☺️
.
.
Had some great matches, and met some great people! Also had a very weird no gi match with a reffing error. I got a tap from my opponent to an armbar and the ref stopped the fight (both the tap and the ref stoppage clearly on video) but for some reason the match kept going after. Don’t worry, after my coach yelled a lot the ref corrected himself in the end 😂. No lesson to be learnt there other than always video your matches so at least you’ve got evidence if you need it 😂😅. 
.
.
Biggest thank you to my coach and partner @fayyazbjj thank you for always coming to my matches, coaching me (even when I don’t listen like a dumdum 😅) and just being my number one supporter ❤️ you make doing this sport even more fun and fulfilling. Another big thank you to my teammates at @profectusbwood who helped prep me 💙
.
.
I’ll update with some video soon!! Thanks everyone for all the well wishes and congratulations ❤️ I genuinely feel so lucky to have so many supportive people around me, and also so many supportive followers, you guys are awesome and brighten my day a lot more than you know
.
.
Thanks again to @hyperfly @hyperflywomen for the comp gear, if you’re a woman looking for good no gi shorts, SERIOUSLY give the hyperfly double layered shorts a go. No riding up, and the built in spandex under layer kept me from worrying 😂👌🏻
 .
.

node.text:
I finally got my dream job at the guillotine factory...
.
.
....I’ll beheading there shortly 😜😬
.
.
What’s the most frustrating part of your sport? 
.
.
I’m headed to Orlando today and will compete Thursday in the gi and Friday in no gi (first time competing in no gi in ibjjf). Really excited to be decked out in new @hyperfly gear to fit the no gi requirements 💙. Previously @hyperflywomen sports bras were my favourite workout gear and now I think it’s the new @onechampionship collab shorts 😍. 
.
So... while I love competing in jiu jitsu and see the need for weight categories, they can be super frustrating for a few reasons (esp as a female). 
.
.
1) No gi weight categories vs gi weight categories are dumb in my opinion 😂. They account for a 6 lbs gi which means that while I can easily make weight for medium heavy in the gi I would struggle to make it in no gi...so I compete in different weight categories for the different disciplines making me hella small for my no gi bracket
.
2) being a female and making weight can be tricky because of our menstrual cycle. Last week I was hanging out in between 155-158 lbs and this week I’m 163 because of my cycle 😡. Unfortunately my body doesn’t follow a 28 day cycle, timing what weight category I should fit into while signing up for a competition doesn’t work as seamlessly as it should on paper. I know this is a struggle a LOT of female athletes who deal with weight brackets share
.
.
So while I love competing in jiu jitsu that’s one big thing I find REALLY frustrating, but understand that it is what it is (and I don’t have any better solution to how it could be done other than decreasing the weight category difference between gi and no gi lol)

node.text:
A mime broke his left arm in a bar fight and got arrested. 

He still has the right to remain silent 🤔😂

What sport do you do and why do you love it? 

I do both triathlon and jiu jitsu, but I often get asked why I love jiu jitsu...I mean you’re covered in your sweat, someone else’s sweat, and this other person is literally trying to choke you unconscious and/or snap one of your limbs. Sounds like fun right? 😂

Once you get over the sweat thing you realize how jiu jitsu is an amazing intricate balance of mental strategy and physicality....and it’s hard to get good at it, it’s a challenge. But the part that keeps me coming back is the community aspect. Not only do you have community in your own gym, but you find it in most BJJ gyms across the world. You can walk into a gym and be welcomed, and feel instantly connected. And most times that connection is even deeper amongst the female jiu jiteras. 

It makes sense. Your average gym will have maybe 1-3 females present per class (often times zero) so when you walk in and see the one other woman on the mats you know you share many of the same struggles and personality traits...I mean you both show up daily to try to fight a room full of men 😂

I’ve noticed competing as a female usually looks very different than what I see  watching the men compete. Prior to and while competing its business, you both want to win and will do your best to win. But once the match is done I most often find respect, support, and camaraderie similar to what you’d find after a roll at an open mat. 

I love this sport so much, and I love the amazing women I’ve met and befriended  worldwide because of it. 
.
.
📸 by @autumn_skye_photography 
.
.
#bjjgirls #bjjlifestyle #bjjlife #jiujitsu #jiujitsugirls #jiujitsugirl #brazilianjiujitsu

node.text:
After posting a story about how I’ve lost 15-20 lbs in the last year I got A LOT of questions in my DMs. 

First off...I want zero comments saying “you look great now that you’ve dropped weight” or “you looked better before” or “you look great at either weight!”. None of these are compliments, and women on the Internet are pretty tired of hearing unsolicited opinions about their bodies. So. Hush. 

With that out of the way 😂...Yes I’ve lost a lot of weight in the last year. I got tons of DMs asking how I dropped it, if I’ve found I’ve lost cardio, have I lost strength. So here we go. 

I lost about 5 lbs during a weight cut for jiu jitsu, this was me simply cutting out Icecream and candy. After competing I went back to my normal eating habits but kept dropping weight. How you ask? Well...my lifestyle changed. I have worked on a bachelors degree and masters degree for the last 10 years, went through trauma, ptsd, and just general stress. And now? My life is a hell of a lot less stressful. This massive drop in stress hormones is what I believe contributed the most to my weight drop. 

I never really knew HOW much of an impact stress had had on my body, I knew I was incredibly chronically stressed but always thought “well this is my body type”. Despite training INSANE hours for triathlon, nothing really changed my body much (although it was never my focus) and I was happy with that. I loved my body then just as I love my body now. 

To ensure it wasn’t another factor I even had my doctor run a series of tests of my hormones, and overall health. The ease of my weight loss was completely lifestyle based. I decreased the stress of my environment, I found a loving and supportive partner @fayyazbjj , and I also escaped Edmonton’s horrible dark winter 😂. 

So no, I didn’t do any crazy diet and I won’t give diet advice either. Changing my stressful lifestyle changed the inner health of both my brain and body. 
.
.
.
